## THE WORLD REACTS: DOG GONE PROFIT HITS THE STREETS

### THE DOGS (THE 64)

**K-9's Reaction**: Mixed. Proud that SD Media is going international, but uneasy. Angel showed up from Oakland, got a feature with K-9, got Zed on the closing track, and now has a 7-track project that positions HIM as the voice of the label's next chapter. K-9 is THE Voice. That's his title. Hearing Angel call himself "the beat reverend" and "I teach the streets penmanship" — K-9 respects the bars but feels territorial. He won't say it out loud. He'll just go harder on his next track. The stutter-flow on Track 03 was K-9 at his most playful — but hearing the finished album back, K-9 realizes Angel kept the stumble in. Was that tribute or exposure? K-9's ad-libs on Track 05 were minimal for a reason — he was observing, not co-signing fully. After hearing the full project, K-9 tells Dame: "It's cold. But man's moving fast for a new dog."

**Zed's Reaction**: Silent approval. Zed gave Angel the benediction on Track 06. That doesn't happen lightly. Zed heard something in Angel that reminded him of himself — carrying dead weight, wearing masks, speaking in code. But Zed is also calculating. Angel's "Reyes Volkov" name on the album is dangerous — it mirrors Zed's Russian cover too closely. If anyone at the Academy hears both a "Russian student at NEPH" AND a "Volkov" on an SD Media album, questions get asked. Zed pulls Angel aside after the first listen: "The name. Change it or bury it. I don't care which. But it can't live on a track and live in a school at the same time." Angel pushes back. Zed doesn't repeat himself. The tension sits.

**Rax's Reaction**: Genuinely excited. Rax doesn't have the territorial ego K-9 has — he sees Angel as proof that SD Media is REAL, that it reaches beyond the ends. Rax is the one who shares it first, playing Track 03 (The Thrizz Session) in the St. Augustine's common room on his phone speaker, just loud enough to make Nala look up. When Alistair asks what that noise is, Rax grins: "Culture, bruv. You wouldn't get it." Rax texts K-9 after: "The Prophet track is hard. You sound good on Track 03 fam." K-9 reads it, doesn't reply for two hours.

**Chew-Toy's Reaction**: Strategic concern. As Dame's successor and the Dogs' operational manager, Chew-Toy thinks in logistics. The album names real people (Dimitri, Trey, Socks, Yay), references RICO, mentions Wormwood Scrubs, and maps a network from Oakland to Chicago to London. This is an evidence file disguised as art. Chew-Toy goes to Snout: "The Prophet album. It's good. It's also a prosecution exhibit if the Met ever pulls the trigger on us." Snout listens, nods, and says nothing — which is how Snout says he agrees.

**Big 9's Reaction** (from Wormwood): Dame plays him the album over the phone, holding it to the speaker. Big 9 listens to all 7 tracks without speaking. When it ends, he says: "The kid from Oakland. He's real." Pause. "But tell him to take my name out his mouth until I say he can put it there." Big 9 respects Angel but hasn't blessed him directly. Being mentioned on Track 05 ("Big ups brother Big 9 cuz you a real 1") without Big 9's explicit permission is a breach of protocol. It's not hostile — it's hierarchy. You don't namecheck the founder until the founder says you can. Dame relays the message. Angel, to his credit, doesn't argue. He just nods: "Entendido."

**Dame's Reaction**: This is HER project. She executive-produced it. She rolled camera on ProphetFilms. She mixed the Lux phone call on Track 06. Dame hears the finished product and knows two things simultaneously: (1) this is the best-produced SD Media project yet, and (2) it cannot drop right now. The Fountain Incident just happened. Police are watching the Plaza. The news already reported on Dogs' "unusual activity." Dropping an album that maps SD Media's international network, features an Oakland fugitive-adjacent MC, and includes Dog-Law commandments would be pouring petrol on a fire. Dame vaults it. Angel doesn't understand. Dame looks at him: "I'm not protecting the album. I'm protecting you. And K. And everyone on that tape. When it's time, it drops. Not before." Angel respects Dame more after this conversation than he did recording with her.

**Snout's Reaction**: Snout doesn't listen to music. Snout listens to implications. He has someone transcribe the lyrics. He reads them like a federal filing. Track 04's Dog-Law commandments concern him — not because they're wrong, but because they're WRITTEN DOWN. The Dogs' code has always been oral, passed down, never documented. Angel just carved it into a track. If this album surfaces, the code isn't secret anymore. Snout's verdict to Dame: "The boy writes like a witness. Teach him to write like a soldier."

