### DAME (THE EXECUTIVE PRODUCER)

Dame's relationship with the album is the most complex because she made it AND she killed it.

**As Producer**: This is her best work. The mournful piano on Track 06 is haunting. The way she mixed K-9's stutter on Track 03 — keeping the stumble, making it feel live and dangerous — is production genius. The 16-voice chant opening Track 04 took her two days to assemble. She's proud.

**As Protector**: She knows what happens when street music gets federal attention. Big 9 is already in Wormwood for life. If Dog Gone Profit surfaces and prosecutors connect Oakland RICO cases to London gang activity through Angel → SD Media → K-9 → Big 9, that's not just bad for Angel. That's bad for Big 9's appeal. That's bad for K-9's freedom. That's bad for every dog on every track.

**As Artist**: Dame watches the ProphetFilms footage and sees herself — young, talented, documenting everything because the camera is the only thing between you and disappearing. She was Angel before Angel arrived. The difference is she learned to control the narrative. Angel hasn't learned that yet. He films everything. He records everything. He puts everything on the album. Dame's job isn't just to produce the music — it's to teach Angel that some things are more powerful when they stay in the vault.

**Dame's Decision**: The album stays vaulted until three conditions are met: (1) Big 9's legal team confirms nothing on the album can be used against him, (2) Angel's Oakland situation is fully cold (no active federal interest), and (3) the Fountain Incident media cycle dies completely. Until then, it's locked in The Kennel's hard drive, encrypted, backed up on a USB in Dame's bra drawer next to Big 9's letters.

