### THE WORLD (THE SCENE / THE INTERNET / THE STREETS)

**If it leaks**: Underground grime forums lose their minds. A Bay Area MC on an SD Media project? With K-9? With ZED? The Track 02 cipher with "The E-Boy" gets analyzed bar for bar. Nobody knows who The E-Boy is — theories range from a SEPH ghost dog to a completely unknown MC to (correctly, by one anonymous poster who gets laughed off) Stray. The Dog-Law commandments from Track 04 become meme content — kids at NEPH start writing them on bathroom walls. "THOU SHALT NOT SNITCH" appears in chalk on the Plaza fountain the next morning. Alistair has it power-washed by noon.

**The Music Press**: UK grime publications are intrigued but cautious. An American on a grime track isn't new, but Angel isn't doing grime — he's doing something between grime, Bay Area hyphy, drill, and spoken word. There's no genre for it. One reviewer calls it "immigrant gospel." Another calls it "transatlantic threat music." The Poe reference on the title track gets picked up by a literary blog that has no idea what SD Media is — they just think the Tell-Tale Heart interpolation is clever. Suddenly Dog-Prophet has readers who've never heard grime in their lives.

**Oakland**: Word gets back to Ghost Town. Angel's old circle — what's left of it — has opinions. Some are proud (hometown kid went international). Some are suspicious (did he snitch his way to London? Is the album a cooperation agreement in disguise?). The dedications to Dimitri, Trey, Socks, and Yay on Track 01 either honor the dead or endanger the living, depending on who's listening. One of Angel's old associates sends a text: "Heard your thing. Sounds good. Take our names out." Angel doesn't reply. He can't. Those names are the only thing keeping those people alive in memory. Removing them would be its own kind of death.

**The Metropolitan Police**: If the album surfaces, it lands on a desk at the Met's Gangs Matrix unit within 48 hours. An analyst transcribes the Dog-Law commandments. They cross-reference "SD Media" with existing intelligence on the Stray Dogs. They note the cross-referencing of Oakland, Chicago, and London — which suggests international organized crime to anyone looking for it. They flag K-9's name. They flag Wormwood Scrubs. They add Angel Reyes to a watchlist. None of this results in immediate action — but it means the next time ANY dog does anything, the response will be heavier. The album doesn't cause a raid. It causes the raid after the raid to be worse.

